Introduction¶

Dataset Source¶

The dataset used for this project was sourced from the UCI Machine Learning Repository (Bank Marketing Data Set, 2014). The information contained in the dataset is about the clients of a Portuguese Bank, dated from May 2008 to November 2010.

Dataset Details¶

The dataset is about the clienteles of a Portuguese Bank. The campaigns held by the bank used phone calls as the mode of converting their normal client into a term deposit client. The folder contains various datasets, but for the purpose of this project we would be using the bank-additional-full.csv file as it contains the complete record of all the leads attained by the bank. The other datasets are a subset of this dataset (Bank Marketing Data Set, 2014).

The dataset in use contains 41188 instances with 21 total attributes (including the target feature 'variable y'). The information contained about the clients includes: age, job, marital status, education, has the client defaulted in credit, and whether the client has housing loan (UCI Machine Learning Repository, 2014).

Additional information: type of contact to the client (telephone or cellular), last month of contact, last contact day of week, the duration of the last call, number of campaigns performed on a particular client, days since the client was last contacted, number of calls performed before this campaign, previous campaign outcome, and other social and economic context attributes such as Employment variation rate (quarterly), Consumer Price Index (monthly), Consumer Confidence Index (monthly), EURIOBOR 3 month rate (daily), and number of employees (quarterly) (UCI Machine Learning Repository, 2014).

The definitions of certain terms have been provided below for attaining a better context to the problem at hand.

Term Deposit: It is a fixed-term investment by a customer that involves the deposit of money into an account in a financial institution.(Investopedia, 2022).

The Consumer Price Index (CPI): It is a type of measurement system that intends to examine the weighted prices of goods. Any deviation in the CPI would affect the cost of living for the people in a country (Investopedia, 2022).

The Consumer Confidence Index (CCI): It takes into consideration how positive the consumers are about spending on goods. It is a directly proportional relationship i.e. more amount of spending by the consumer would result in benefiting the society (Investopedia, 2022).

Dataset Features¶

Before we begin with the exploration of the data, let us describe all the features of the dataset in a tabular form below. Please note that these details have been sourced from the file bank-additional-names.names file present within the same data folder retrieved from the UCI Machine Learning Repository (UCI Machine Learning Repository, 2014).

S.No Feature Name Data-Type Units Description Domain

21 y Binary Not Applicable Has the client subscribed a term deposit Yes, No

Target Feature¶

For this project, the target feature is the 'variable y' (categorical), which is a binary attribute, yes means the client subscribed for a term deposit, and no means the client rejected the offer. The outcome of the target feature will be predicted (in phase-2) using the descriptive features that we have in hand.

Goals and Objectives¶

A marketing campaign is performed either to get new leads or to convert a lead into a customer. Any banking institution that can predict to a certain accuracy who might become their valuable client will help cut down costs, and in turn use those finances for other services.

A term deposit sign-up by a customer means that the bank now has more cash flow coming in, which would in-turn be used to provide loans. A customer gets the benefit of receiving interest on his/ her investment, the time-period of which is decided by the bank.

Note: The observations in this dataset are not correlated.

As we can see that there were 10,700 observations with one of the above-mentioned features having unknown as an input value. Also from the earlier calculations we found that a total of 12,718 unknowns existed i.e. 2018 rows did have multiple unknowns in them.

After removing the rows, we now have 30,488 rows left, still a significant amount of data to predict from.

4. Dropping any irrelevant or redundant attributes¶

From an inspection of the dataset attributes, we can see all the attributes are desired for predicting the outcome of the target variable y except duration. Although duration highly affects the outcome of the output variable y, the feature should be dropped the reason being that the duration cannot be known before a call is placed.

Hence, we will drop the duration feature for the purposes of predictive modelling.

In [ ]:
# Dropping duration attribute

clients = clients.drop(['duration'],axis =1)
clients.shape
Out[ ]:
(30478, 20)

We can see that the duration feature has been dropped, and the total number of columns are now 20.

1.4 Histogram for Feature: Age¶

Age being a numerical feature, a count plot would not be able to represent an accurate information about what most of the age-set is because of the abundance of values in the dataset. Hence, we will use a histogram to understand the dynamics of the age feature.

In [ ]:
# Histogram for Age 

mean_of_age = clients['age'].mean() 

sns.histplot(x='age', data = clients, bins= 30, color = 'grey')
plt.axvline(mean_of_age, color ='purple', linestyle ='--') # Marking the mean on the plot 
plt.title ('Plot 4. Histogram for the variation of age')
plt.xlabel('Division of Age') 
plt.ylabel('Count of Age Range')

plt.show()

As we can see that majority of our clients in the dataset belong between the ages of 30 and 40, and the histogram is skewed to the right i.e. a positive skew, we can say that the mean is being pulled towards the higher values. Considering this is a decently skewed data, and hence mean may not best define the central tendency of the plot.

Summary and Conclusion¶

In the context of a bank, being able to know beforehand what customers are likely to subscribe for a term deposit account can be immensely beneficial. From how marketing has changed over the years from cold calls to being able to bid so that an advertisement is shown to a customer, technology has been the means to-do-so. With every improvement, an organisation is trying to secure customers for itself.

In this particular case-study, it contains data from the year 2008 to 2010, the period when the housing market crashed. Considering that context, for banks at that time it would have become imperative to secure clients for long term deposits.

The goals of this project are to predict what type of customers are like to subscribe to a term deposit with a bank using the bank marketing dataset of a Portuguese Bank, and that what descriptive features are most suitable for doing so.

This report pertains to the phase-1 of this project, and tasks such as data cleaning and preprocessing were performed along with data exploration and visualizations. In the Data Wrangling process, we:

  1. First, we dropped all the missing values, as such there were not any missing values specified via NA or NaN but marked as unknown in attributes job,education,marital_status, housing,loan, and default, and we dropped them citing their contribution was less as compared to the rest of the dataset.
  2. We then moved-on to remove all (10) the duplicate observations as they would not have any contribution for the predictive analysis process.
  3. Further, we dropped the duration attribute as the value of this cannot be known before a call is placed, although the attribute would have had an effect on the outcome of the target feature, it does not provide a benefit for predicting the outcome, as this field would depend upon the data from the customer care executive or the marketing team. This model intends to predict without the use of the duration feature.
  4. There were not actually any wrong values but there were two observations with age as 17, which we dropped considering the client is yet not an adult, and would not be able to subscribe to a term deposit account.
  5. Columns such as marital and y were renamed to marital_status and term_deposit. There were attributes with a . (period) in them, and that was replaced by an _ (underscore).

After the Data Cleaning and Preprocessing process, we also plotted several visualizations in order to better understand the data at hand. The visualizations were divided into one-variable, two-variable, and three-variable plots.

From the one-variable plots, we inferred that 12.7% of the total clients had taken a subscription, majority of the clients were employed as admins, and most of the clients held a university degree. Majority of the dataset was formed by the clients between the ages of 30 and 40. 96% of the clients were new i.e. never contacted before this campaign, and most of the clients were contacted between 0 and 10 times during this campaign.

From the two-variable plots, we observed that as the cons_price_idx increased the outcome of the target variable term_deposit shifted towards the negative. More people subscribed for a term deposit when the emp_var_rate went down, and none of the people who had defaulted on their loans had taken a subscription. Clients only started to subscribe to term_deposits when the cons_conf_idx had touched -53. The Euribor3m rate reduced considerably over-time, and as it did the cons_conf_idx also went down, hence term_deposit subscription went down.

From the three-variable plots, the clients (50 Percentile) who had not defaulted on their loans subscribed to a term_deposit when cons_conf_idx had touched -43. We also observed a correlation between social and economic features such as emp_var_rate, and nr_employed.
